Even though a divorce can be laid at the feet of a marriage that did not work, creating tension between a husband and wife should never be viewed as a single doorway to failure. Married couples often lose sight of this in Peru and some carry their personal issues into the public sphere, which is a clear violation of Samsara.

Samsara is an important part of living in Peru for the married couples of Cusco. In practice, it is the strong belief that life on Earth is not the end. Personal transgressions such as a failed marriage are a natural part of life and instead of seeing a divorce as ending the overall happiness, Peruvians see it as another element in the cycle. Transcending the effect of a divorce on the marriage is natural in Peru.

The Celibate Way in Samsara

Cusco is a place where large families rule the day. Every decade or so, families see the birth of many children that bring extended generations of family members into their ranks. This is a major influence on the average living conditions for families in Peru and many households are the norm.

Married couples of Peru do not share any difficulties or complexities associated with a need to find an acceptable mate. On the contrary, taboo in Peru is all about abstinence and self-examination
